    <li class="publication featured article">
  <cite><span class="title">
  <span>Sr Betavoltaic Power Source.</span>
  <i>Scientific reports</i>
</span>
<span class="authors">Dixon, J., Rajan, A., Bohlemann, S., Coso, D., Upadhyaya, A. D., Rohatgi, A., Chu, S., Majumdar, A., Yee, S.</span>

<span class="details">
   <span class="year">2016</span>; <span class="volume">6</span><span class="pages">: 38182-?</span>
</span></cite>
    <div class="detail">
      <h4>Abstract</h4>
  <p class="abstract">Betavoltaic energy converters (i.e., Î²-batteries) are attractive power sources because of their potential for high energy densities (&gt;200â€‰MWh/kg) and long duration continuous discharge (&gt;1 year). However, conversion efficiencies have been historically low (&lt;3%). High efficiency devices can be achieved by matching Î²-radiation transport length scales with the device physics length scales. In this work, the efficiency of c-Si devices using high-energy (&gt;1â€‰MeV) electrons emitted from (90)Sr as a power source is investigated. We propose a design for a &gt;10% efficient betavoltaic device, which generates 1â€‰W of power. A Varian Clinac iX is used to simulate the high-energy electrons emitted from (90)Sr, and a high efficiency c-Si photovoltaic cell is used as the converter. The measured conversion efficiency is 16%. This relatively high value is attributed to proper length scale matching and the generation of secondary electrons in c-Si by the primary Î²-particles.</p>
  <p class="doi">
    <span>View details for <a href="/https://dx.doi.org/10.1038/srep38182">DOI 10.1038/srep38182</a></span>
  </p>
  <p class="pub-med">
    <span>View details for <a href="/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27905521">PubMedID 27905521</a></span>
  </p>
  <p class="pub-med-central">
    <span>View details for <a href="/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5131278">PubMedCentralID PMC5131278</a></span>
